  "text": "Although lentiviral (LV) vectors have been successfully used to transduce both T cells and NK-cell lines, LV transduction of both freshly isolated and ex vivo-expanded NK cells may be challenging. Chimeric antigen receptors (CARs) are synthetic engineered receptors that target surface molecules in their native conformation, independent of MHC and of antigen processing by the target cells [CITATION_1] . The generations of CARs are typically classified based on the intracellular signaling domains, with first-generation CARs including only CD3ζ, second-generation CARs including one single costimulatory domain and third-generation CARs including two costimulatory domains, such as CD28 and 41BB.",
